<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-336-104  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 336 104.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  June 12 1989 v35 n1762 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sanctioning dependency. (proposed US trade restrictions againstJapan) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The opposition of major US electronics firms to the proposed tradesanctions against Japan exposes the extent of our dependency onsuperior Japanese technology.andP;  The proposed trade sanctions are inresponse to Japan's failure to keep its promise to open itsdomestic electronics market to foreign competition, but theJapanese products that have been targeted for sanctions areessential to the survival of the US electronics industry.andO;Die-bonders, flat screen displays, steppers and photolithographyproducts from Japan are technologically superior to competing USproducts and, without them, US companies will no longer be able toproduce any products that are technically equivalent to theirJapanese counterparts.andP;  Unless rigid sanctions are imposed,however, it will be easier for US companies to buy than to create,and the country will lose its technological leadership in everyarea of electronics.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     JapanUnited StatesTelecommunicationsExportInternational TradeSemiconductorsElectronics.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>